Here's the registration and the reasoning:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient — singleton so you reuse connections / socket pooling
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // DataService — singleton because it wraps HttpClient and holds
        // no per-user/per-page state; one instance serves the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets a fresh instance
        // with its own state (avoids stale data between navigations)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient for the same reason: each navigation push
        // creates a new page bound to its own ViewModel
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | Singleton | Avoids socket exhaustion from repeated creation |
| `IDataService` | Singleton | Stateless API wrapper — one instance is enough and it keeps a consistent `HttpClient` reference |
| ViewModels | Transient | Each page navigation needs fresh state; a singleton would leak data between visits |
| Pages | Transient | MAUI pages hold UI state — reusing them causes binding/lifecycle bugs |

> **Tip:** If `DataService` ever held per-user session state (e.g., auth tokens that change), `Scoped` would be appropriate instead — but in MAUI, scoped and singleton behave identically unless you manually create scopes, so singleton is the pragmatic default for shared services.
